### Step 4.2 — Create a Web Page Reader Tool

```java
@Component
public class WebPageReaderTool {

    @Tool(description = "Read and extract the main text content from a web page URL. Use this to read documentation pages, blog posts, or API references that you found via web search.")
    public String readWebPage(
        @ToolParam(description = "The full URL to read, e.g. 'https://docs.spring.io/...'") String url
    ) {
        try {
            HttpRequest request = HttpRequest.newBuilder()
                .uri(URI.create(url))
                .header("User-Agent", "AgentManager/1.0")
                .timeout(Duration.ofSeconds(15))
                .GET()
                .build();

            HttpResponse<String> response = httpClient.send(request, HttpResponse.BodyHandlers.ofString());

            // Strip HTML tags, keep text content
            String text = stripHtml(response.body());

            // Truncate to prevent context overflow
            if (text.length() > 20000) {
                text = text.substring(0, 20000) + "\n\n... [TRUNCATED]";
            }

            return text;
        } catch (Exception e) {
            return "ERROR: Failed to read page: " + e.getMessage();
        }
    }

    private String stripHtml(String html) {
        // Remove script/style tags and their content
        html = html.replaceAll("<(script|style)[^>]*>.*?</\\1>", "");
        // Remove HTML tags
        html = html.replaceAll("<[^>]+>", " ");
        // Normalize whitespace
        html = html.replaceAll("\\s+", " ").trim();
        return html;
    }
}
```

